    <header class=3D"prose entry-header">
        <h1 class=3D"entry-title">An Intuitive (and Short) Explanation of B=
ayes=E2=80=99 Theorem</h1>    </header>

    <div class=3D"prose entry-content overflow-clip">
        <p>Bayes=E2=80=99 theorem was the subject of <a href=3D"http://www.=
yudkowsky.net/rational/bayes">a detailed article</a>. The essay is good, bu=
t over 15,000 words long =E2=80=94 here=E2=80=99s the condensed version for=
 Bayesian newcomers like myself:</p>

<ul>
<li><p><strong>Tests are not the event.</strong> We have a cancer <em>test<=
/em>, separate from the event of actually having cancer. We have a <em>test=
</em> for spam, separate from the event of actually having a spam message.<=
/p></li>
<li><p><strong>Tests are flawed.</strong> Tests detect things that don=E2=
=80=99t exist (false positive), and miss things that do exist (false negati=
ve). People often use test results without adjusting for test errors.</p></=
li>
<li><p><strong>False positives skew results.</strong> Suppose you are searc=
hing for something really rare (1 in a million). Even with a good test, it=
=E2=80=99s likely that a positive result is really a <em>false positive</em=
> on somebody in the 999,999.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>People prefer natural numbers.</strong> Saying =E2=80=9C100 =
in 10,000=E2=80=B3 rather than =E2=80=9C1%=E2=80=9D helps people work throu=
gh the numbers with fewer errors, especially with multiple percentages (=E2=
=80=9COf those 100, 80 will test positive=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9C80%=
 of the 1% will test positive=E2=80=9D).</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Even science is a test</strong>. At a philosophical level, s=
cientific experiments are =E2=80=9Cpotentially flawed tests=E2=80=9D and ne=
ed to be treated accordingly. There is a <em>test</em> for a chemical, or a=
 phenomenon, and there is the <em>event</em> of the phenomenon itself. Our =
tests and measuring equipment have a rate of error to be accounted for.</p>=
</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Bayes=E2=80=99 theorem converts the results from your test into =
the real probability of the event.</strong> For example, you can:</p>

<ul>
<li><p><strong>Correct for measurement errors</strong>. If you know the rea=
l probabilities and the chance of a false positive and false negative, you =
can correct for measurement errors.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Relate the actual probability to the measured test probabili=
ty.</strong> Given mammogram test results and known error rates, you can pr=
edict the actual chance of having cancer given a positive test. In technica=
l terms, you can find Pr(H|E), the chance that a hypothesis H is true given=
 evidence E, starting from Pr(E|H), the chance that evidence appears when t=
he hypothesis is true.</p></li>
</ul>

<div style=3D"position:relative;height:0;padding-bottom:56.25%"><iframe src=
=3D"cid:frame-28ACABDB6A3B35CC95AFB5CA42956D40@mhtml.blink" width=3D"640" h=
eight=3D"360" frameborder=3D"0" style=3D"position:absolute;width:100%;heigh=
t:100%;left:0" allowfullscreen=3D""></iframe></div>

<h2>Anatomy of a Test</h2>

<p>The article describes a cancer testing scenario:</p>

<ul>
<li>1% of women have breast cancer (and therefore 99% do not).</li>
<li>80% of mammograms detect breast cancer when it is there (and therefore =
20% miss it).</li>
<li>9.6% of mammograms detect breast cancer when it=E2=80=99s <strong>not</=
strong> there (and therefore 90.4% correctly return a negative result).</li=
>
</ul>

<p>Put in a table, the probabilities look like this:</p>

<p><picture><source srcset=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/webp-e=
xpress/webp-images/uploads/math/bayes/bayes_table.png.webp" type=3D"image/w=
ebp"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/=
uploads/math/bayes/bayes_table.png" alt=3D"bayes table" title=3D"bayes_tabl=
e.png" class=3D"webpexpress-processed"></picture></p>

<p>How do we read it?</p>

<ul>
<li>1% of people have cancer</li>
<li>If you already have cancer, you are in the first column. There=E2=80=99=
s an 80% chance you will test positive. There=E2=80=99s a 20% chance you wi=
ll test negative.</li>
<li>If you don=E2=80=99t have cancer, you are in the second column. There=
=E2=80=99s a 9.6% chance you will test positive, and a 90.4% chance you wil=
l test negative.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How Accurate Is The Test?</h2>

<p>Now suppose you get a positive test result. What are the chances you hav=
e cancer? 80%? 99%? 1%?</p>

<p>Here=E2=80=99s how I think about it:</p>

<ul>
<li>Ok, we got a positive result. It means we=E2=80=99re somewhere in the t=
op row of our table. Let=E2=80=99s not assume anything =E2=80=94 it could b=
e a true positive or a false positive.</li>
<li>The chances of a <em>true positive</em> =3D chance you have cancer * ch=
ance test caught it =3D 1% * 80% =3D .008</li>
<li>The chances of a <em>false positive</em> =3D chance you don=E2=80=99t h=
ave cancer * chance test caught it anyway =3D 99% * 9.6% =3D 0.09504</li>
</ul>

<p>The table looks like this:</p>

<p><picture><source srcset=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/webp-e=
xpress/webp-images/uploads/2017/01/bayes_table_computed_new_png.png.webp" t=
ype=3D"image/webp"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://betterexplained.c=
om/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/bayes_table_computed_new_png.png" alt=3D"baye=
s table computed" class=3D"webpexpress-processed"></picture></p>

<p>And what was the question again? Oh yes: what=E2=80=99s the chance we re=
ally have cancer if we get a positive result. The chance of an event is the=
 number of ways it could happen given all possible outcomes:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/ee5390894367d1b1711d23786f6eca84.png" width=3D"232" height=3D"41=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{ \text{Probability} =3D \frac{\text{desired event}}{=
\text{all possibilities}} }" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p>The chance of getting a real, positive result is .008. The chance of get=
ting any type of positive result is the chance of a true positive plus the =
chance of a false positive (.008 + 0.09504 =3D .10304).</p>

<p>So, our chance of cancer is .008/.10304 =3D 0.0776, or about 7.8%.</p>

<p>Interesting =E2=80=94 a positive mammogram only means you have a 7.8% ch=
ance of cancer, rather than 80% (the supposed accuracy of the test). It mig=
ht seem strange at first but it makes sense: the test gives a false positiv=
e 9.6% of the time (quite high), so there will be many false positives in a=
 given population. For a rare disease, most of the positive test results wi=
ll be wrong.</p>

<p>Let=E2=80=99s test our intuition by drawing a conclusion from simply eye=
balling the table. If you take 100 people, only 1 person will have cancer (=
1%), and they=E2=80=99re most likely going to test positive (80% chance). O=
f the 99 remaining people, about 10% will test positive, so we=E2=80=99ll g=
et roughly 10 false positives. Considering all the positive tests, just 1 i=
n 11 is correct, so there=E2=80=99s a 1/11 chance of having cancer given a =
positive test. The real number is 7.8% (closer to 1/13, computed above), bu=
t we found a reasonable estimate without a calculator.</p>

<h2>Bayes=E2=80=99 Theorem</h2>

<p>We can turn the process above into an equation, which is Bayes=E2=80=99 =
Theorem. It lets you take the test results and correct for the =E2=80=9Cske=
w=E2=80=9D introduced by false positives. You get the real chance of having=
 the event. Here=E2=80=99s the equation:</p>

<p><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/ColorizedMath=
/img/Bayes_Theorem.png" alt=3D"bayes theorem colorized equation"></p>

<p>And here=E2=80=99s the decoder key to read it:</p>

<ul>
<li>Pr(H|E) =3D Chance of having cancer (H) given a positive test (E). This=
 is what we want to know: How likely is it to have cancer with a positive r=
esult? In our case it was 7.8%.</li>
<li>Pr(E|H) =3D Chance of a positive test (E) given that you had cancer (H)=
. This is the chance of a true positive, 80% in our case.</li>
<li>Pr(H) =3D Chance of having cancer (1%).</li>
<li>Pr(not H) =3D Chance of not having cancer (99%).</li>
<li>Pr(E|not H) =3D Chance of a positive test (E) given that you didn=E2=80=
=99t have cancer (not H). This is a false positive, 9.6% in our case.</li>
</ul>

<p>Try it with any number:</p>

<iframe src=3D"cid:frame-78768252AE55331729A6077A66E908D0@mhtml.blink" fram=
eborder=3D"0" marginwidth=3D"0" marginheight=3D"0" width=3D"450" height=3D"=
300"></iframe>

<p>It all comes down to the chance of a <em>true</em> positive divided by t=
he chance of <em>any</em> positive. We can simplify the equation to:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/abb9243a6a7d838ec02cc5f9713e5604.png" width=3D"206" height=3D"44=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\Pr(\mathrm{H}|\mathrm{E}) =3D \frac{\Pr(\mathrm{E}|=
\mathrm{H})\Pr(\mathrm{H})}{\Pr(\mathrm{E})}}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p>Pr(E) tells us the chance of getting <em>any</em> positive result, wheth=
er a true positive in the cancer population (1%) or a false positive in the=
 non-cancer population (99%). In acts like a weighting factor, adjusting th=
e odds towards the more likely outcome.</p>

<p>Forgetting to account for false positives is what makes the low 7.8% cha=
nce of cancer (given a positive test) seem counter-intuitive. Thank you, no=
rmalizing constant, for setting us straight!</p>

<h2>Intuitive Understanding: Shine The Light</h2>

<p>The article mentions an intuitive understanding about shining a light th=
rough your real population and getting a test population. The analogy makes=
 sense, but it takes a few thousand words to get there :).</p>

<p>Consider a real population. You do some tests which =E2=80=9Cshines ligh=
t=E2=80=9D through that real population and creates some test results. If t=
he light is completely accurate, the test probabilities and real probabilit=
ies match up. Everyone who tests positive is actually =E2=80=9Cpositive=E2=
=80=9D. Everyone who tests negative is actually =E2=80=9Cnegative=E2=80=9D.=
</p>

<p>But this is the real world. Tests go wrong. Sometimes the people who hav=
e cancer don=E2=80=99t show up in the tests, and the other way around.</p>

<p>Bayes=E2=80=99 Theorem lets us look at the skewed test results and corre=
ct for errors, recreating the original population and finding the real chan=
ce of a true positive result.</p>

<h2>Bayesian Spam Filtering</h2>

<p>One clever application of Bayes=E2=80=99 Theorem is in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_spam_filtering">spam filtering</a>. We hav=
e</p>

<ul>
<li>Event A: The message is spam.</li>
<li>Test X: The message contains certain words (X)</li>
</ul>

<p>Plugged into a more readable formula (from Wikipedia):</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/da59f0597e5b97578af81ba86fe6dc3e.png" width=3D"358" height=3D"44=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\Pr(\mathrm{spam}|\mathrm{words}) =3D \frac{\Pr(\mat=
hrm{words}|\mathrm{spam})\Pr(\mathrm{spam})}{\Pr(\mathrm{words})}}" class=
=3D"tex"></p>

<p>Bayesian filtering allows us to predict the chance a message is really s=
pam given the =E2=80=9Ctest results=E2=80=9D (the presence of certain words=
). Clearly, words like =E2=80=9Cviagra=E2=80=9D have a higher chance of app=
earing in spam messages than in normal ones.</p>

<p>Spam filtering based on a blacklist is flawed =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s too=
 restrictive and false positives are too great. But Bayesian filtering give=
s us a middle ground =E2=80=94  we use  <em>probabilities</em>. As we analy=
ze the words in a message, we can compute the chance it is spam (rather tha=
n making a yes/no decision). If a message has a 99.9% chance of being spam,=
 it probably is. As the filter gets trained with more and more messages, it=
 updates the probabilities that certain words lead to spam messages. Advanc=
ed Bayesian filters can examine multiple words in a row, as another data po=
int.</p>

<h2>Further Reading</h2>

<p>There=E2=80=99s a lot being said about Bayes:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27s_theorem">Bayes=E2=80=
=99 Theorem on Wikipedia</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/000850.html">Discu=
ssion on coding horror</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"http://www.yudkowsky.net/rational/bayes">The big essay on Ba=
yes=E2=80=99 Theorem</a></li>
</ul>

